Rating: 0
To those of you looking for the "Olive Garden Pasta e Fagioli": 1 lb ground beef, 1 small onion, diced (1 cup), 1 lg carrot, julienne (1 cup), 3 stalks celery, chopped (1 cup), 2 cloves garlic, minced, 2 (14.5 oz) cans diced tomatoes, 1 (15 oz) can red kidney beans (with liquid), 1 (15 oz) can great northern beans (with liquid), 1 (15 oz) can tomato sauce, 1 (12 oz) can V-8 juice, 1 T white vinegar, 1½ tsp salt, 1 tsp EACH oregano and basil, ½ tsp EACH pepper and thyme, ½ lb(½ pkg) ditali pasta. Brown beef in a lg saucepan over med heat. Drain off most of the fat. Add vegetables and sauté for 10 mins. Add remaining ingredients, except pasta, and simmer for 1 hr. About 50 mins into simmer time, cook pasta in 1½ to 2 quarts of boiling water over high heat. Cook for 10 mins or just until pasta is al dente. Drain. Add pasta to soup. Simmer for 5-10 mins and serve. Serves 8.

Rating: 4
Instead of bacon!! Go to your local butcher shop and ask them to save the end of a parma proscuitto for you. Boil the proscuitto end in a pot of water until the water reduces 3 times. Keep adding water until you get a pork broth. Once it reduces the third time use this as your stock. Then in a side saute, start your onion, garlic, carrot, celery. Follow recipe above, once you have added all your beans, and veggie saute, then add your chopped prosciutto back to your soup. Do not add the pasta until you are ready to serve, sprinkle Peccorino romano instead of Parmesean. The procuitto gives the soup a hearty pork flavor without the fatty bacon greese. I make this soup every winter and serve with crusty bread. Oh.... I am going to make it right now!

